'''Mukul S. Anand''' ([[11 October]], [[1951]] - [[7 September]] [[1997]]) was an [[Indian film]] director and producer. He was the nephew of veteran film scriptwriter [[Inder Raj Anand]] and cousin of actor and director [[Tinnu Anand]]. 

==Career==
Mukul S. Anand's films were known for being visually stunning and were often shot at spectacular locations. He made his debut as a director with ''[[Kanoon Kya Karega]]'' in 1984. His most notable films included ''[[Sultanat]]'' (1986), ''[[Agneepath]]'' (1990), ''[[Hum (film)|Hum]]'' (1991) and ''[[Khuda Gawah]]'' (1992). For ''Khuda Gawah'' he won the [[Filmfare Best Director Award]]. His last completed film was the critical and box office failure ''[[Trimurti (film)|Trimurti]]'' in 1995. He also produced but did not direct ''[[Army (film)|Army]]'' in 1996.

==Personal life==
Inder Raj Anand who was a film scriptwriter from the late 1940s through to the late 1980s was Mukul Anand's uncle. Mukul's cousin was actor and director [[Tinnu Anand]].
Mukul was married to Anita and had two children Alishka and Mikhail.
[http://www.mukulsananddreamsgalore.com/FILMOGRAPHYANDUTAHLOCATIONSHOOT.html]

Mukul died of a [[heart attack]] at the age of 45 in September [[1997]]. At the time of his death he was in the middle of filming the action movie ''[[Dus (1997 film)|Dus]]'' in [[Utah]]. The climax scenes and some action sequences were being filmed in May and June of 1997 and 40% of the shooting had been completed by August 1997. The film was left incomplete after his death and never released. Promo videos and clips from what was shot of the film can be seen on his official website which is maintained by his wife Anita and sister Beena. 

In 2005 the producer of ''Dus'' [[Nitin Manmohan]] decided to make another film with the same title and two of the stars of ''Dus'' [[Sanjay Dutt]] and [[Shilpa Shetty]] also starred in that film.

